    "content": "NOW — The terminological decisions, convention debates, and philosophical rationales behind our choices are at their sharpest right now. If we wait until after full translation, we will reconstruct these from memory or notes, and the reasoning will be less precise. A draft now captures the living logic of decisions like the 德 split, the \"phenomenal X\" convention, the register hierarchy, and the block-quote format while the deliberations are still fresh. It also serves a practical function during translation: having the preface as a working document keeps the team aligned on governing principles as we move through new passages. The revision after completion is inevitable regardless — new issues will arise, some decisions may evolve — but revising a substantive draft is far better than writing from scratch after the fact."
